text:
Tony Strack notified me, it appears the Page Speed Insights tester built into the extension is returning different results than the page speed insights website.

I’m guessing that Google likely updated their API, but I’m not 100% sure on that.

So just a heads up for the short term don’t trust the extension’s scores completely.
<https://github.com/TheWebTech/HubSpot-Developer-Extension/issues/230>
yup looks like they updated their api, might be a simple fix
Also, when testing on that in general, google will sometimes give you two scores if you run it twice. So those arent always consistent in general.
I just updated the API version that we’re using and the scores are still wildly different
(mobile shows 75) where as it shows as 98 in the extension.

it just straight up returns different data. not sure what to think of those “scores” google gives I can say what’s cool is the api returns a lot of data now. Though I’ll be honest I don’t think it’s worth actually displaying all of that. If someone wants a comprehensive performance test that’s what the audits tab is for
Might be easier to just have the page speed insights button link off to the pagespeed URL with the current URL appended. <https://developers.google.com/speed/pagespeed/insights/?url=[url-of-site]>
not a bad idea. That’s a simple enough thing to do
just figure it's be easier as Google is providing alot more info now in those insights
yea. and I can get actually almost all the data they return through the api but honestly, idk what to think of it if the base score is not consistent lol
i know though i def get different results if I run a page, then wait 5 mins and run it again so the tool itself isn't consistent.
like i ran our homepage, got a 83 waited about 3-4 mins, now i got an 87
lol yea. I mean I get like server response times might shift very slightly so I understand maybe a up to a 4 pt change
but I’m seeing a 75 on the web page for mobile and a 98 in the extension
goes to tell clients to ignore Google’s web page and just use the extension
